This tool is the 'deep diagnostic' for plugin issues. The handler needs to:

1. Look up plugin metadata via getPluginMeta(pluginName) — get URL patterns and expected adapter hash
2. Find all matching tabs: query chrome.tabs with the plugin's URL patterns
3. For each tab, run chrome.scripting.executeScript to inspect the adapter:

```javascript
const ot = globalThis.__openTabs;
if (!ot || !ot.adapters || !ot.adapters[pluginName]) {
  return { adapterPresent: false };
}
const adapter = ot.adapters[pluginName];
let isReady = false;
try {
  const result = adapter.isReady();
  isReady = result instanceof Promise ? await result : !!result;
} catch { isReady = false; }
return {
  adapterPresent: true,
  adapterHash: adapter.__adapterHash || null,
  toolCount: Array.isArray(adapter.tools) ? adapter.tools.length : 0,
  toolNames: Array.isArray(adapter.tools) ? adapter.tools.map(t => t.name) : [],
  isReady,
};
```

4. Compare adapter hash to expected hash from metadata
5. Aggregate results per tab

For finding matching tabs, reuse the matchPattern function from tab-matching.ts. Query all tabs with chrome.tabs.query({}), then filter by URL pattern matching.

The isReady() call needs a timeout wrapper. Use Promise.race with a 5-second timeout, matching IS_READY_TIMEOUT_MS.

Run tab checks in parallel (Promise.allSettled) to avoid O(N * timeout) latency.

